      'titulo' => 'Actions to promote and protect the mental health of the elderly in primary health care',
      'conteudo' => 'The growing increase in the population of the elderly worldwide leads to the need to rethink the current organization of society to deal with this reality, which more specifically affects health services. In Brazil, this population grew rapidly and significantly, reaching a level of 13.5% of the total population in 20181.

      The concern about these people arises from the multiple physical, emotional and social changes that make them more susceptible to the presence of various diseases and changes in the state of health that are characterized by their chronicity and complexity, which interferes with the quality of life, therefore requiring attention.
      
      In the elderly population, mental health problems, attributed to stressful events, the presence of diseases, disabilities and social isolation, deserve to be highlighted. A study conducted in the state of Northeast Brazil showed a general prevalence of 55.8% of elderly people with common mental disorders, with the most symptoms being: freeze easily and feel nervous, tense or worried, which is related to depressive mood2.
      
      In addition, social representations of health professionals and the community work together to confuse the mental health problems of the elderly with the natural process of aging, undermining diagnosis and treatment3.
      
      They contribute to mental health problems among the elderly: social isolation, death of close people, the presence of multiple diseases, advancement of age, as well as factors such as low schooling, whether of the female sex. Faced with this, it is suggested that health professionals be empowered to act alongside these people in an interdisciplinary way, guiding themselves in actions to promote health. From this perspective, primary health care (PHS) represents a favourable scenario4.
      
      The International Plan of Action on Ageing (IPAP), with regard to the mental health of the elderly, provides for the development of strategies that promote the early identification and treatment of people in mental distress. The PIAE aims to develop educational and public awareness-raising actions to promote healthy ageing and strengthen the network of care and support for the elderly involving the family and the community5.
      
      APS is responsible for solving much of the needs. It is thus expected that the health needs of the elderly will be met in their entirety. For this purpose, in addition to the basic teams that integrate the units of the Family Health Strategy (ESF), they have the Amplified Nucleus of Family Health and Basic Care (NASF-AB), which operate as a multi-professional and interdisciplinary team of integrated intervention to the APS teams. Mental health professionals are added to the teams6.
      
      The Psychosocial Care Centers (CAPS), being reference services in mental health, should also operate in the logic of matrix support to the APS teams. However, it recognizes the challenge of strengthening them in the practice of services, essentially with regard to actions to promote health7.
      
      In the evaluation of the performance of the comprehensive care of the elderly in the APS, held in 68 municipalities within the state of São Paulo, it was found that the actions of promotion and prevention are incorporated in few services and in an incomplete manner, and although there is consensus on the relevance of these actions, the practices are restricted to the care of chronic non-communicable diseases (CNS)8.
      
      Similarly, attention to the mental health of the elderly in PSA is configured by outpatient care practices and the presence of a conceptual transition in the vision about the aging process and mental health9.
      
      Despite successful experiments with the implementation of ESF, the disease-centred vision persists, mainly in relation to the elderly population, prevailing the biomedical model of health care10. Movements are identified for the expansion of actions to promote mental health in the APS. However, they are still early in the tensioning of actions in the psychosocial perspective11.
      
      Faced with the above, it is understood that there is a need to translate the challenges of the production of care into mental health and to enhance territorialized care, considering the importance of advancing in the promotion of health and in the prevention of aggravations to the mental health of the elderly. Thus, the objective is to analyse the actions of promotion and protection of the mental health of the elderly person in the context of primary care available in the literature.'
